How will you differentiate between a class and a struct?

a class is a reference type and stores on the heap;
a struct is a value type and is stored on the stack;

a struct doesn't support inheritance and polymorphism;
a class does;

a class can be of an abstract type;
a struct can't;

all members of a class are private be default
all members of a struct are public be default

The distinction between class and struct which is based on memory management is that the former supports garbage collection while the latter doesn't.

